<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 10:24<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I295dd720630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>10.</label.designator><headtext>Documentary and Demonstrative Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id7212890682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>10:24.</label.designator><headtext>The jury view</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The trial court has discretion regarding whether to grant a jury view and its ruling will seldom be reversed on appeal.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7b20094074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] The judge may order a view over the objection of a party[<footnote.reference refid="I7b20094174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] or on his own motion.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7b20094274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>] The court may properly grant a view of personal property.[<eos/><?page no="388"?><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7b20305074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The judge does not have to attend the view, especially when neither party requested it.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7b20305174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Federal due process does not require that a criminal defendant be present at a view,[<footnote.reference refid="I7b20305274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">6</footnote.reference>] but Georgia requires that the criminal defendant attend or waive his right to be present.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7b20305374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">7</footnote.reference>] In a civil case, the defendant has no right to be present at a “scene” view.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7b20305474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">8</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>A motion for a view and any objection thereto should be made out of the hearing of the jury.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7b20305574d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">9</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Georgia Supreme Court held it erroneous for a judge to hear evidence on an interlocutory injunction regarding a view without the knowledge or consent of either party.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7b20576074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">10</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1981111564" w-seq-number="00029" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1fa6114274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Jordan v. State</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I7b20576174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">11</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Supreme Court distinguished two types of jury views: (1) the “evidentiary view” and (2) “the scene view.” <eos/><bos/>The scene view is not “evidence.” <eos/><bos/>The evidentiary view is to <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“permit the jury to view evidence introduced in the case, which evidence is so large or affixed that it cannot be brought into the courtroom.”<eos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1981146877" w-seq-number="00031" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1fa6fba274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>McDaniel v. State</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="I7b20576274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">12</footnote.reference>] followed <cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1981111564" w-seq-number="00033" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1fa80d1274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Jordan</ital></cite.query><?page no="389"?> in considering the view of the scene of the crime a scene view. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1987083197" w-seq-number="00034" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1fa80d1574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Harper v. State</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="I7b20576374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">13</footnote.reference>] continued this distinction by holding that a scene view was not evidence and that the trial judge need not so charge the jury in the absence of a request, but the jury could use the view by applying it to the testimony.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>It is reversible error for jurors to take an unauthorized view.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7b207e7074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">14</footnote.reference>] <cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1986102010" w-seq-number="00038" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1fa993b274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Forney v. State</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="I7b207e7174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">15</footnote.reference>] was an unusual case in which the jury foreman asked if four jurors could view the scene of the crime since eight jurors had gone to the scene on their own. <eos/><bos/>In upholding the trial judge&apos;s decision to order the entire jury to take a proper view, the Georgia Supreme Court distinguished the cases in which the jurors viewed the scene without court intervention.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="I7b20094074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>View denied in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1976136033" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1f9e491274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Sutton v. State, 237 Ga. 418, 228 S.E.2d 815 (1976)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1977113925" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1f9e491574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Lingerfelt v. State, 238 Ga. 355, 233 S.E.2d 356 (1977)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1980109978" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1f9e491874d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Williams v. State, 153 Ga. App. 421, 265 S.E.2d 341 (1980)</cite.query> (trial judge <case.history>denied</case.history> a view even though the jury requested a view).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1980109769" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1f9ebe4274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Flynt v. State, 153 Ga. App. 232, 264 S.E.2d 669 (1980)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>View granted in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1976136475" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1f9f0c6274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Weeks v. DeKalb County, 140 Ga. App. 15, 230 S.E.2d 79 (1976)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1979128618" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1f9f0c6574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Sipple v. Fowler, 151 Ga. App. 135, 259 S.E.2d 142 (1979)</cite.query> (court approved a view a number of years after the event in issue); <cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1980138054" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1f9f0c6874d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Palmer v. State, 155 Ga. App. 368, 271 S.E.2d 24 (1980)</cite.query> (same).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b20094174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1902010778" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I1f9f819274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Bibb County v. Reese, 115 Ga. 346, 41 S.E. 636 (1902)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1935107347" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I1f9f819574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Moore v. Macon Coca-Cola Bottling Co., 180 Ga. 335, 178 S.E. 711 (1935)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b20094274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1984102102" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1f9fcfb274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Pritchett v. Anding, 168 Ga. App. 658, 310 S.E.2d 267 (1983)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b20305074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator><?page no="388"?>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1980138054" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1fa044e274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Palmer v. State, 155 Ga. App. 368, 271 S.E.2d 24 (1980)</cite.query>, involving a view of a truck.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1981111564" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1fa1565274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5"><?page no="388"?>Jordan v. State, 247 Ga. 328, 276 S.E.2d 224 (1981)</cite.query>, the court cited the <cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1980138054" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1fa1565574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Palmer</ital></cite.query> case and other cases from the court of appeals involving views of motor vehicles with apparent approval.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1982100865" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1fa1a47274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Martin v. State, 160 Ga. App. 275, 287 S.E.2d 244 (1981)</cite.query>, involved a view of an automobile.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1987077019" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1fa1f29274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Self v. State, 182 Ga. App. 656, 356 S.E.2d 722 (1987)</cite.query>, the trial judge had not abused his discretion in denying a view of a van outside the courthouse. <eos/><bos/>A photograph was introduced.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>However, in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1978144469" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1fa240b274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Megar v. State, 144 Ga. App. 564, 241 S.E.2d 447 (1978)</cite.query>, the trial judge had <case.history>denied</case.history> a request for a jury view of an automobile. <eos/><bos/>The court held that such a view was a matter of discretion which had not been abused in this case.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b20305174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1945103853" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1fa2b5e274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Shahan v. American Tel. &amp; Tel. Co., 72 Ga. App. 749, 35 S.E.2d 5 (1945)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b20305274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1934124471" w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000104" ID="I1fa3522474d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Snyder v. Com. of Mass., 291 U.S. 97, 54 S. Ct. 330, 78 L. Ed. 674, 90 A.L.R. 575 (1934)</cite.query> (<case.history>overruled in part on other grounds by</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1964124849" w-seq-number="00019" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="I1fa3522774d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Malloy v. Hogan, 378 U.S. 1, 84 S. Ct. 1489, 12 L. Ed. 2d 653 (1964)</cite.query>).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b20305374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1923105819" w-seq-number="00020" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I1fa3c75274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Chance v. State, 156 Ga. 428, 119 S.E. 303 (1923)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1975131567" w-seq-number="00021" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1fa3c75574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Harwell v. England, 234 Ga. 640, 217 S.E.2d 154 (1975)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1975132149" w-seq-number="00022" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1fa3c75874d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Durrett v. State, 135 Ga. App. 749, 219 S.E.2d 9 (1975)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b20305474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1984102102" w-seq-number="00023" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1fa4157274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Pritchett v. Anding, 168 Ga. App. 658, 310 S.E.2d 267 (1983)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b20305574d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>9</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1945103853" w-seq-number="00024" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1fa48aa274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Shahan v. American Tel. &amp; Tel. Co., 72 Ga. App. 749, 35 S.E.2d 5 (1945)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1958122503" w-seq-number="00025" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1fa48aa574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Leverett v. Awnings, Inc., 97 Ga. App. 811, 104 S.E.2d 686 (1958)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1969134312" w-seq-number="00026" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1fa4ffd274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Hill v. Dixie Pipeline Co., 120 Ga. App. 82, 169 S.E.2d 656 (1969)</cite.query>, a motion for a view was made by the plaintiff in the presence of the jury. <eos/><bos/>The defendant immediately objected without requesting that the jury withdraw. <eos/><bos/>The court held that the defendant had not been forced to object in the presence of the jury.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b20576074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>10</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1906011556" w-seq-number="00027" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I1fa5750274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Atlantic &amp; B. Ry. Co. v. City of Cordele, 125 Ga. 373, 54 S.E. 155 (1906)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1954105249" w-seq-number="00028" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1fa5750574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Brown v. Transcontinental Gas Pipe Line Corp., 210 Ga. 580, 82 S.E.2d 12 (1954)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b20576174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>11</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1981111564" w-seq-number="00030" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1fa65f6274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Jordan v. State, 247 Ga. 328, 276 S.E.2d 224 (1981)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b20576274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>12</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1981146877" w-seq-number="00032" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1fa722b274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">McDaniel v. State, 248 Ga. 494, 283 S.E.2d 862 (1981)</cite.query><?page no="389"?>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b20576374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>13</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1987083197" w-seq-number="00035" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1fa8342274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Harper v. State, 182 Ga. App. 760, 357 S.E.2d 117 (1987)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b207e7074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>14</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>It was error for two jurors to take an unauthorized view, measure time intervals of travel during the trial, and report their observations to the other jurors. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1976136271" w-seq-number="00036" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1fa8d06274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Watkins v. State, 237 Ga. 678, 229 S.E.2d 465 (1976)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1985114262" w-seq-number="00037" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1fa91e8274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Bobo v. State, 254 Ga. 146, 327 S.E.2d 208 (1985)</cite.query>, two jurors visited the crime scene and related their findings to the jury. <eos/><bos/>This misconduct was prejudicial error and the court reversed the conviction.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7b207e7174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>15</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017222" w-serial-number="1986102010" w-seq-number="00039" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1fa9bac274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Forney v. State, 255 Ga. 316, 338 S.E.2d 252 (1986)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 10:24<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
